    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p>Office of Ezekiel &#38; Co.<lb/>
            Auction and Commission Merchants&#44;<lb/>
            Nos. 19 &#38; 21 West Pearl Street<lb/></p>
            <p>Cincinnati&#44; May 21. 1877.<lb/></p>
            <p>Rev S. Morais.<lb/>
            My valued friend&#33;<lb/></p>
            <p>The sun is powerful<lb/> here to day&#44; too warm to write&#44;<lb/> but I thought of an old motto<lb/> I used to read on one of Phila<lb/> Hose carriages&#44; when a boy&#44; and<lb/> it was simply this.  &#34;When duty<lb/> calls&#44; &#34;Tis ours to obey.&#34;  Well now<lb/> the fact is&#44; I have been with the<lb/> Doctor for a couple of hours&#44; and<lb/> speaking about college affairs &#38;<lb/> the prospects for a new class for<lb/> the next session.  I spoke to him<lb/> about the larger boys at the<lb/> &#34;Foster Home&#34; at Phila of the oppor<lb/>tunity that now affords <del>here</del><lb/> for those who are far advanced<lb/> enough in Eng &#38; Hebrew to enter<lb/> the college here&#44; and desire to<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>to get a Eng &#38; Hebrew collegiate<lb/> education.  I mean those who<lb/> wish&#44; to come as indigent students<lb/> they will be well provided for<lb/> during the whole time they are<lb/> here&#44; with all the <sic>neccessaries</sic><lb/> of Life&#44; can attend Hebrew College<lb/> every day&#44; High School or Univer&#45;<lb/>sity all without charge&#44; it may<lb/> require from 4 to 8 years study&#44;<lb/> see what an opportunity is now<lb/> <sic>offerred</sic> for poor young man&#44; the<lb/> Doctor requested me to write to you<lb/> that in case any of the boys<lb/> may desire to embrace the oppor<lb/>tunity now <sic>offorred</sic>&#44; and who may<lb/> require a little extra study of<lb/> the Hebrew&#44; to be admitted into the<lb/> college&#44; that you might now have<lb/> <del>appl</del> ample time to prepare them<lb/> for the next session.  I named the<lb/> Foster Home boys because they<lb/> being trained by discipline&#44; will<lb/> make good scholars&#44; but if you<lb/> know any other poor young men&#44;<lb/> who desire to study&#44; let them make<lb/></p>
            
            <pb n="3"/>
            <p>early application for admission<lb/> and I will attend to it&#44; as a<lb/> matter of course we cannot take<lb/> but a few more indigent students<lb/> for the next class.  We have now<lb/> 12 that we support costing us<lb/> from 5 to 6000 dollars a year<lb/> we might take 5 or 6 more the<lb/> coming session&#44; so we thought<lb/> to write to you.  I would like to<lb/> give Philadelphia the preference<lb/> as we will meet there this <del>July</del><lb/> July&#44; therefore I let you know<lb/> in time&#44; by this opportunity you<lb/> can do an act of charity to a<lb/> few that may be deserving.<lb/>  I often wish that when I was<lb/> young&#44; that such a chance<lb/> would have offered itself to me.<lb/></p>
            <p>I hope this may meet you well&#44;<lb/> with the dear ones.  Tell dear<lb/> Nina her letter reached me in<lb/> time for this week.<lb/></p>
            <p>I will write more anon<lb/>
            Truly as Ever&#44;<lb/>
            Jacob Ezekiel<lb/></p>
        </body>
    </text>
